  array('ID' => '107','H_ID' => 'H137','Makers_Name' => 'Hardy','Model' => 'Alma','Sub_Model' => NULL,'Size' => '4 3/4','Approx_date' => '1926','Foot' => 'Äluminium','Handle' => 'Ebonite','Tension_Regulator' => 'Early 2 speed','Details' => 'Produced in very limited numbers from 1925 to 1936, the Hardy Alma reel is the first two speed big game reel ever offered commercially, the brainchild of Charles Alma Baker, C.B.E. (Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire). According to his book Rough Guide to New Zealand Big Game Fishing, Baker had the idea of a two-speed reel as early as 1916, and worked to perfect it through the years, with numerous prototypes tested by the likes of Zane Grey and Alma Baker himself, until satisfied that the new reel would withstand the rigors of landing big game fish worldwide. The first production model, offered in 1925 through the Hardy Catalogs, was made using ebonite side plates, as this rare 4 3/4" diameter reel has, later changing over to an all aluminum framed reel in the late 1920\'s. Numbers of these ebonite sided, 4 3/4" diameter reels, as reported in John Drewett\'s definitive book on early Hardy reels, Hardy Brothers - The Masters The Men and Their Reels, were limited to just 17 reels, 11 produced in 1926 and only 6 made in 1927 (one aluminum sided reel of this size was made in 1934). Features of this engineering marvel are best described by the write up in the Hardy catalog, with mention of the "Capstan Star" drag, free spool, 1:1 or 2 1/2:1 retrieve ratios obtained via the gear change lever mounted on the face plate, leather thumb brake and two optional click checks of differing strengths, operated by turn buttons on the tail plate that could be used separately or together, providing a total of three variations of check. With two pinned crescent shaped plaques affixed to the tail plate, one with "The Alma Reel - Made by Hardy Bros Ltd - Alnwick, England", the other listing the various patents, "Pat. Nos. G.B.231100. Can. 251344. N.Z. 53518. U.S.A. 1559927. Pat App. For in Australia", this very good plus to excellent minus condition reel functions perfectly, having light to moderate evidence of use, with mottled surface corrosion to the spool flanges and arbor, a hole in the full length foot, and a tiny rim chip near the 9 o\'clock pillar screw and light to moderate sun fading.','Hcondition' => 'VG to excellent with a corroded spool, small chip to one screw pillar','SerialNo' => NULL,'Date_Purchased' => '04/2019','Price_paid' => '6150','Valuation' => '10000','date_sold' => NULL,'sale_price' => NULL,'sold_to' => NULL,'sold_to_email' => NULL),
